snippet: Even former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has embraced the goals of the Green New Deal, showing just how far the Democratic field has moved on climate change.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Joseph R. Biden Jr. was Barack Obama’s vice president, their administration brokered the landmark Paris climate accord and imposed the nation’s first federal regulations for cutting carbon dioxide emissions.
abstract: Even former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has embraced the goals of the Green New Deal, showing just how far the Democratic field has moved on climate change.

snippet: David Garrow found F.B.I. documents alleging King stood by during a rape. But some scholars question whether to trust records created as part of a smear campaign.
lead_paragraph: When David J. Garrow, a Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., sat down last spring to dig through a trove of previously unreleased government records, it was business as usual for a researcher known for prodigious reporting and doorstop books.
abstract: David Garrow found F.B.I. documents alleging King stood by during a rape. But some scholars question whether to trust records created as part of a smear campaign.

snippet: In the absence of hardball questions, Mr. Buttigieg delved into policy, at points appearing to work through the details of his ideas in real time.
lead_paragraph: Pete Buttigieg thrives in town halls: It was one of them, on CNN in March, that initially sent him near the top of what is now a 23-person Democratic presidential field. But this one was different.

headline_main: Pete Buttigieg Finds a Friendly Crowd at MSNBC Town Hall

snippet: Stumbling blind into the age of diversity.
lead_paragraph: For much of the 20th century, young and old people voted pretty similarly. The defining gaps in our recent politics have been the gender gap (women preferring Democrats) and the education gap. But now the generation gap is back, with a vengeance.

snippet: After California moved its primary up by three months, it could prove to be the linchpin for almost any Democratic path to the 2020 nomination.
lead_paragraph: Good Monday morning. Here are some of the stories making news in Washington and politics today.
abstract: After California moved its primary up by three months, it could prove to be the linchpin for almost any Democratic path to the 2020 nomination.
headline_main: On Politics: California Is Now an Early Primary State

snippet: Quotation of the Day for Monday, June 3, 2019.
lead_paragraph: “The problem with California is that you could spend, like, hundreds of millions of dollars and it will feel like you spent five pennies.”
abstract: Quotation of the Day for Monday, June 3, 2019.
headline_main: Quotation of the Day: In California, Democrats Try for Early Prize

snippet: A Sunday town hall with Senator Kirsten Gillibrand was another sign of Fox News’s ability to influence the Democratic primary, despite a ban by party leaders.
lead_paragraph: Three months ago, Democratic Party leaders took a stand: Fox News, President Trump’s favorite channel, and a reliable soapbox for attacks on liberals, was barred from participating in the party’s 2020 presidential debates. The move would ice out the network derided by critics as “state TV” from influencing the outcome of the Democratic primary.
abstract: A Sunday town hall with Senator Kirsten Gillibrand was another sign of Fox News’s ability to influence the Democratic primary, despite a ban by party leaders.

snippet: My political agenda has been shaped by my family’s experiences of struggling to make ends meet.
lead_paragraph: My father came to this country from Poland at the age of 17 with barely a nickel in his pocket. I spent my first 18 years, before I left home for college, in a three-and-a-half-room, rent-controlled apartment in Brooklyn. My mother’s dream was to own her own home, but we never came close. My father’s salary as a paint salesman paid for basic necessities, but never much more.
